column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste arrived at Clean Harbor's in-transit storage facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quanttities of hazardous waste onto a signle transport vehicle for continued transportation. Upon arrival at the location, the driver opened the back door and found material had leaked onto the floor of the trailer.  An emergency response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The leak was contained with absorbent pads and floor dry.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container along with the materials used in the cleanup.  The trailer was cleaned with a cleaning compound and placed back into service.  The salvage drum was then loaded onto another trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, the container was inspected and no evidence of damage or leaking was observed.  It was determined, however, that a foreign object pounctured the bottom of the container during transportation allowing the material to escape from the package.  In order to prvent a recirrence, the driver has been re instructed to insure that the trailer floor is swept ourt beofre loading to remove any items that could impact the structural integrity of a container during transportation and/or storage.

column168: We ordered and received Hanna item 93701-F which was a special order for us.  Upon reviewing the MSDS we found the material has a 10% concentration of Sodium Hydroxide and Section 14 of Hanna's MSDS identified it as a DOT regulated material which we agree with.  The box was completely unmarked with respect to the regulated chemical.  It could have been processed using Limited Quantity, ORM-D or the 173.4 Small Quantity Exception, but none of these were marked on the package. We've called this supplier in the past regarding this issue and have been told due to the small quantity involved they did not have to do anything.  We disagree and will apply the required communication when we ship the product out to our customer.

column168: GATX 24072 was interchanged to the PTRA at Pasadena Yard on 10/5/2009. The tank car was switched into track 14 on the same day where it sat until it was discovered leaking on 10/6/2009 at approximately 1350 hrs. A PTRA switchman was riding a shove movement on track 15 past the leaking tank and observed the leak. He reported that the vapors from the leak made him dizzy and gave him a headache. He reported the leak to the yardmaster and trainmaster on duty. The employee was transported to a doctors office where he was observed and released. He was advised to take aspirin as necessary for his headache. No other restrictions or instructions were listed. The doctor did not release him for duty account the employee wanted a second opinion by his personal doctor on 10/7/09.  The PTRA safety Director arrived on scene at 1411 hrs. He notified M&M Protection Services to respond to the incident upon arrival. M&M arrived on scene at 1510 hrs.  Responders released the pressure on the tank and stopped the leak from the manway cover. Upon further investigation it was discovered that the car was overloaded and had a damaged/torn gasket. The product level was 1/4 inch from the top of the manway. The weather was approximately 92 degress and mostly sunny allowing the product to expand and leak out around the manway. A vacuum truck was ordered to transfer the product until a proper outage was reached in the tank car.  While waiting for the vacuum truck M&M had to allow the pressure to release on the tank car. In order to do so they had to maintain a controlled leak. Most of the product that ran down the sides of the car vaporized before hitting the ground. Product on the ground was soaked up using absorbent pads.  The vacuum truck arrived at approximately 1710 hrs. The leak was stopped as soon as the transfer began at approximately 1745 hrs. A total of 1500 gallons was transfered into the vac truck in order to acheive a 15-18 inch outage in the tank car. Upon completion a replacement gasket was applied to the manway and the car was closed and secured for transit to the customer.  The scene was cleared at 1840 hrs. An estimated 15 gallons of product was spilled from the tank. Any product that did not vaporize was soaked up by the absorbent pads. Both the pads and product in the tank truck will be disposed of properly by M&M Protection.
column169: PTRA is working with the TX Haz Mat inspector and the shipper to correct the problem and prevent similar issues in the future. We will discuss the shippers procedures to calculate the proper outage based on the temperature variations across the transportation route. Additionally, we will work with the shipper to ensure the tank car is properly sealed to avoid damage to the gasket and leakage of product.

column168: Carrier driver was directed to the unloading area by the plant operator. driver uses a tractor mounted product pump and his product hoses to transfer the product from the tank trailer to the customers storage tank. the vehicle is located outdoors and the storage in located in the tank building and is out of the drivers view. the driver had the plant operator verify the tank capacity and confirm the amount to be delivered would fit. driver made all connections and with the operators permission started the transfer of material. the cargo tank was almost empty when the operator directed the driver to shut down that the storage tank had overfilled. The spilled material was contained within the tank containment area. No one was exposed to or injured by the material. An estimated ten gallons of material was released.
column169: This release was due to an error in plant procedure.  the night shift had was directed to pump down the storage tank to make way for the product delivery in the morning. the storage tank would not hold the amount shipped in this was not completed. The pump down did not occur and was not communicated to the operator assigned to service our driver. When the operator accepted the load he assumed the pump down occurred. the storage tank was only able to hold 90% shipped and overflowed.    The storage tank has no high level alarm system. the operator must visually inspect the level and the operator failed to do that prior the product transfer.    Delivery driver are directed by the carrier to stay in attendance of their vehicle during product transfer. The customer storage tank operation is the operator responsibility.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While at the Circle K Truck Stop in Opelika, Alabama, the driver discovered free product leaking from the back of the container.  The driver applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the impacted asphalt surface.  The Opelika Fire Department Hazmat Unit responded to assess the site.  After obtaining authorization to open the container doors, the Opelika Fire Department Hazmat Unit entered the container and applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the container floor.  Southern Waste Services of Birmingham, Alabama was dispatched to perform the remainder of the cleanup.  Southern Waste Services arrived on-site and performed a thorough investigation of the container.  Southern Waste Services discovered one (1) leaking 5-gallon metal pail.  Approximately 3 gallons of free product were released from the pail.  Apparently the release was due to faulty packaging.  Southern Waste Services placed the leaking pail into a 55-gallon recovery drum for disposal.  Southern Waste Services applied additional absorbent material as needed and recovered all spent absorbent material.  The spent absorbent material was placed into the 55-gallon drum containing the leaking pail.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Bridge Terminal Transport, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: On 10/01/09, 02:15 hours, CSXT employee Derek Barton, General Car Foreman, Radnor yard, Nashville, TN, reported tank car TILX 303024, a load of Anhydrous Ammonia, leaking from the top of the car.  The rail car was located on track A-7 in the receiving yard. The Nashville Metro Police Department was notified and responded. The shipper was also notified of the incident. A CSXT emergency response contractor, SWS, and Hazardous Materials Manager, Jim Briski, responded to the scene. Upon arrival, SWS personnel found the A-end liquid line valve was open 1/4 turn and the closure plug was less than tool tight. SWS representatives closed the valve, tightened the plug and the leak stopped.  The car was decontaminated and forwarded on to destination. A CSXT mechanical employee, was taken to the local hospital as a precautionary measure, examined, released and returned to work with no medication or restrictions.     No special switching move was performed.  A 7.1 Non conformance report is not required.    Cause Code:  119  Narri: 5 (5+10-+2) x (2+2) = 340

column168: On October 5, 2009 at 22:00 hrs, personnel in the CSXT Tilford Yard discovered GAMX 9845, a loaded tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-10-05-00203). Bill Caton and Chris Machenberg, CSXT hazardous materials managers, were dispatched to the scene and found the B-end liquid line leaking at the valve stem. The packing was adjusted and tightened and the product subsequently began leaking at the closure plug.  The plug was tool tight but lacked sealant material. Therefore, the car was transloaded into Tanner Industries trucks onsite. A vacuum was drawn on the car to facilitate safe removal of the plug and an to properly reseat the valve. Sealant tape was applied to the closure plug to mitigate further release.  RESCAR was contracted by the car owner to repair faulty packing found on the A-end liquid line during transloading procedure. This incident did require a special switching move.  Cause Code:  296  NARRI:  5(5+9+0) x (2+0) = 140

column168: Driver noted leakage from trailer while en route and stopped to investigate, noting spill of approximately 15 gallons in trailer with a small amount escaping past trailer secondary containment dike. Driver contained spilled material using absorbents and local soil until response crew arrived, at which time leaking drum was identified and material was recovered into salvage drum(s). Leaking drum was discovered to have thin area which had failed in transit. Drum specification markings wee not discernible.  Spilled material was largely contained within trailer. Based upon amount recovered, it is estimated that approximately 3 gallons tctal were released from trailer, with in excess of two gallons released at location of trailer stop, and subsequently recovered from shoulder.  Leaks were determined to be slow leaks from “pin” holes through drum sidewall in corroded/abraded area not evident from drum exterior.
column169: Shippers must ensure integrity of packaging’s used for shipment of hazardous materials, and must also ensure that UN/DOT specification markings are readily visible. In the interest of proper package securement, drums are often shrink-wrapped to skids, el1fectively preventing the complete inspection of those drums. When a single drum is part of a larger consolidated shipment that is pre-loaded, the carrier has little opportunity to visibly inspect every drum; in many cases, such inspections are impracticable if not impossible. The problem is exacerbated when a carrier is not the first carrier to take pos4ession of the materials, as was the case in this incident.   While every effort is made to ensure the proper transportation of hazardous materials, the entire process begins with the ship.  The shipper therefore has the greatest responsibility for and influence on the success of the transport.  As a result, greater emphasis must be placed upon proper packaging selection by the shipper.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was prepared and loaded by representatives of both the shipper and the motor carrier.  Once the initial loading was complete, the driver initiated the movement of the shipment to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a Clean Harbor’s in transit storage facility for the purposes of consolidating less than truck load quantities onto a single vehicle for continued transportation.  During the consolidation process, it was noticed that the closure of one of the containers was not properly secured and it allowed approximately 8 ounces of material to escape onto the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel, utilizing appropriate personal protective equipment, secured the closure device and decontaminated both the container and the floor of the van trailer. The materials generated as a result of the incident were containerized and placed into storage pending off-site disposal
column169: At the time the containers were prepared for transport,loading personnel had inspected the closures and did not identify an issue.  It is belived that when the containers were loaded by means of a mechanical fork-lift that the ringof one drum caught the ring of another and dislodged the closure device.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the river has been instructed to inspect each container as it is loaded to insure that it is positioned in such a way that other freight cannot be loaded in a way that could impact the closure device.

column168: At approximately 1135 the dispatcher was notified that a spill had occurred in which 3 gallons of 38% Sodium Bisulfite had leaked out of a cracked pipe onto the roadway in Gatlinburg, TN.  Marion Environmental was dispatched to clean up this spill.  Assistant Fire Chief, Charlie Cole of Gatlinburg, was incident commander on the scene.  Clean up began at 1316 and was completed at 1600 with no adverse effects to the environment or community.  It was determined that a nut was missing from a "U" bolt.  This "U" bolt securred a 2" vent line attached to a 1" PVC air pipe. The loose U" bolt allowed the vent line to vibrate during transit cracking the PVC pipe and breaking the 2" vent line.  This vent line had not been purged of all the product therefore spilling the 3 gallons on the roadway.
column169: Replacing the piping on this tanker  Installing an automatic valve in place of the manual valve currently on top of the tanker as an added security measure  Retrain the driver that all piping and hoses MUST be void of product before leaving the delivery area. column168: Delivery hose was connected to remote fuel fitting. Driver took opening stick readings from the main fill pipe on the underground fuel tank, replacing the fuel cap when completed. Driver returned to tanker, opened the unloading valve and heard a pop noticing fuel was spilling from the mail fill pipe which he reset after taking his stick reading. The unloading valve qas quickly shut, 911 called with spill containment and clean up initiated. Adams MA Fire Department arrived on scene with a Department of Public Works vehicle laying sand down to contain product and preventing from entering any storm drain or outfall. Emergency response clean up was provided by Maxymillian Technologies of Pittsfield, MA. The MA Department of Ennvironmental Services was notified and assigned Release Tracking # 1-17610. All told 10-15 gallons were released which resulted from the driver not resetting the main fill cap securely prior to unloading to the remote fill fitting.
column169: Instruction provided to double and triple check securement of all fittings prior to opening unloading valves.

The package was transported by air in container number AYY3620FX, a pure container bound for Rock Springs Wyoming. The packages were loaded onto feeder A/C N796FE.  After loading the package onto the feeder it was discovered leaking.  The manager stopped the onload, contacted feeder A/C maintenance and had all unaffected packages loaded onto a different A/C while feeder maintenance inspected the A/C for possible damage caused by the spill.  There were three boxes from this shipper,only one was leaking.  When opening the leaking box we discovered a box inside with class 8 label and a FedEx DG inspection sticker from a previous shipment.  DG Administration (Mike Chambers) was contacted.  He took the product code and name and found the MSDS on the Kodak website.  All three boxes contained the same material.  This undeclared DG was reported to Drew Strabala, FAA agent in Denver.  He said he could not make the long distance trip and requested we send the 5800 and take specific photos of everything.
column169: Mike Chambers contacted the shipper and spoke with Lee Rivera.  She said they were not trained or certified and did not know what to do with this chemical. The Manager at Most Healthcare has decided to not ship this chemical any longer but let Kodak ship for them.  This shipper had the same chemical shipment leaving Wyoming on Sep 18 that did not have a shipper's declaration form.  Our office assisted them to produce the documentation and send it to Wyoming so the package could move to New Jersey.  The package was reinspected and accepted to send to their office in Voorhees, NJ.  We informed them not to ship DG again until they were trained.  THAT shipment was the same package found inside the leaking box going from Voorhees back to Wyoming because it still had the tracking number and DG inspection sticker on it.  They clearly do not know what they are doing and did not heed our warning not to ship DG again.  DG Administration is considering a prohibition of package shipping by this company.  The FedEx Station manager in New Jersey that supports this customer was informed to advise the pick up courier to bring ANY packages from Most Healthcare to the DG inspector for spot checking.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon opening the trailer doors, a leak was discovered in the trailer. column168: On 10/02/2009 at 14:15 hours, personnel in the CSXT Stanley Yard in Walbridge, OH  discovered PLCX 224844, a loaded tank car of Elevated Temperature Liquid, Flammable, NOS (Petroleum Oil) leaking from the top of the car. The shipper, BP Amoco Oil, as well as the Wood County Fire Department were notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2009-10-02-00119). CSXT trainmaster and hazardous material Sentinel, Eric Erickson responded to the scene and found 4 of 8 manway cover securement bolts were less than tool tight.  Mr. Erickson also discovered that the securement bolt nuts were of differing sizes. Mr. Erickson made all the manway cover bolt nuts tool tight.  BP Amoco responded, replaced the odd sized manway bolt nuts and decontaminated the sides of the tank car. The car was then released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60

column168: 10/19/09, approximately 945AM: While performing track work in class yard, CR M+W personnel noted tank car GATX 68163, load Waste Flammable Liquid, Toxic, NOS (D018), class 3, UN1992, PGIII, leaking at the top of the car when it was classified and coupled into another car on track 17 Class.  Car was not actively leaking while standing still.  The 24-hour phone number on railroad movement document was contacted (Heritage Environmental Services, 1-800-326-1221).  As information, tank car reportedly arrived at Conrail's Pavonia Yard on CSXT train Q41718 on October 19, 2009 at 0232hrs.    Further inspection by Conrail's Risk Manager A. Richter, and Conrail's emergency response contractor R.Gould of REACT Environmental Services revealed the following: (manway cover safety bolt cable seal "SYS 017077" intact; protective housing/breadbox cover cable seal "SYS 017076" intact); Seven of eight manway cover securement bolts less than hand tight; one of eight manway cover securement bolts was not applied; and, the manway cover gasket was missing.      After contact with both shipper and consignee personnel on compatiblity, a Viton manway nozzle gasket was applied, and manway cover was closed and secured tool tight.  Inspection of fittings under protective housing/breadbox cover conducted and no exceptions noted.  REACT seal 002325 applied to the manway cover safety bolt, and REACT seal 002130 applied to the protective housing/breadbox cover.  Due to product residue on top and sides of this car that had been released; and additionally had splashed onto boxcar CSXT 129858 (load wood pulp/not powerded), both cars were moved to the Pavonia Carshop onto track 2-Heavy.  Both cars decontaminated/powerwashed on Tuesday, 10/20/09.  Product residue noted on ground was surface affected only, and was remediated on 10/19/09 and handled for disposal by REACT.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a Clean Harbors 10-day in transit storage facility to consolidate less than truckload quantities of hazardous wastes for continuing transportation.  During the transfer activities, the container feel off a pallet when the fork-lift entered the trailer and the force of the fall bent the side of the container dislodging the closure device.  AS a result, approximately 15 gallons of material was released onto the floor of the van trailer and the concrete dock.  Facility personnel immediately donned appropriate protective equipment and placed the damaged container into suitable salvage drum.  An absorbent material was used to recover all material released and this spill clean-up residue along with decontamination media was placed in the salvage drum and was prepared for continued transportation.  Once the response was complete, the drum was loaded and was sent for disposal as originally intended.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the individual responsible for operating the fork-lift has been re instructed on the the proper preparations to use when transferring materials using mechanical container management equipment.  He was also cautioned on speed and sapce management while operating a fork-lift and to ensure each container is positioned in such a way that it will remain stable while being moved.

column168: On 10/02/09 at 1303 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Flomaton, AL yard discovered GATX71757, a loaded tank car of Crude Sulfate Turpentine, leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Georgia Pacific, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-10-02-00106). SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, and Hazardous Materials Manager, Chris Machenberg, were dispatched to the scene and found product leaking from around the threads of the outlet nozzle reducer. Upon further inspection, it was found that the bottom outlet nozzle reducer was loose and the top operated bottom outlet valve was also loose. The packing gland nut was loose and the operating rod was less than tool tight. The valve and packing gland nut was secured.     The bottom outlet nozzle reducer was removed and product was still leaking from the outlet valve in the form of a steady drip. Inspection of the gasket in the outlet nozzle reducer found the gasket material had deteriorated and failed. Also, the secondary valve  was clogged with hardened residue material that could not be removed. SWS replaced the gasket, the leak stopped and the car was decontaminated.  Due to the defective valve, the shipper transferred the car into trucks. The car is awaiting movement approval to a repair facility. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code:  580  NARRI:  5(5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60
column169: Car was transferred to trucks by contractor SWS. The shipper needs to examine all gaskets and fittings prior to loading the car.

column168: On 10/12/09 at 1024 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Gentilly yard in New Orleans, LA discovered GATX 22642, a loaded tank car of Crude Sulfate Turpentine, leaking from around the dome area. The car was isolated and shipper, Boise Cascade, LLC, was contacted. The state police (Report #09-05-656) and the fire department were contacted by the local trainmaster. USES, a CSXT emergency response contractor, and CSX Hazardous Materials Manager, Chris Machenberg, were dispatched to the scene and found two bolts on the manway to be less than tool tight. USES personnel tightened the two bolts and the leak stopped.  The car was decontaminated and released for transport. There was no evidence of any product on the ground surface. This incident did require a special switching move to the spill containment pan.     Cause Code:  200  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60
column169: CSX Hazardous Materials Manager, Chris Machenberg, spoke with Johnny Sharp, the Shipper, about procedures for manway securement. It was discovered that the shipper tightens the bolts in a circular pattern, tightening every other bolt. Mr. Sharp was told to use a star pattern for tightening manway bolts.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the ten day storage yard at the intended waste disposal facility.  Two hours after arrival, while making a routine yard inspection, it was noticed that black liquid was dripping from the trailer onto the packed soil parking area.  A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and found that a cubic yard box was leaking.  The trailer was moved to the dock at the intended waste disposal site and unloaded.  The contaminated soil was cleaned up and placed into a suitable salvage drum along with the contents of the box which were contaminated with paint that had leaked from a paint can contained within the cubic yard box.  The trailer was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service. All material was immedialtey procress for dispoal at the disposal facility.
column169: During the response it was discovered that the closure device on a paint can that was collected from a household hazardous waste collection event came loose during transportation and spilled its contents into the interior of the cubic yard container.  The material leaked through the liner and fiberboard box onto te floor of the van trailer.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the filed crew responsible for laoding this contsainr have been re-instructed on the terms and conditions of the DOT Special Permit authorizing this packaging methodolgy.  Specifically, it was stressed that all containers must be secured, loaded in such a way to prevent movement within the package and packaged in such a way to insure they remain upright within the outer container.

column168: 1. At about 16:55, warehouse agent (Mr. Villanueva) who was offloading skids containing Drums of  Dangerous Goods on to a pallet; afterwards he noticed that on of the skids was overlapping out of the pallet, he decided to use another smaller skid to elevate the skid that contained the DRUMS. As he tried to raise the skid the left blade of the forklift PUNCTURED the bottom of one of the drum, causing a SPILL.2. Incident occurred at 17:00, called Port Authority at 17:08, Call HAZCHEM at 17:11 and left 4 messages around 17:12 for HAZCHEM. Spoke to Mr. John and Jim at SPILL Centre. ISA arrived at 18:30, all information about the incident was given to inspector Fallen at 18:40. FAA (Mr. Steve) was informed at 19:00. Port Authority dispatched to EMERGANCY RESPONSE TEAM which in turn they contained the SPILL and repacked the damaged steel drum into another drum to prevent it from more leaking at 19:00. Sargent G. Martinez gave the authorization to use the warehouse at 20:00. The team of HAZMAT arrived at 20:15 to complete the clean up (speedy dry, etc.).3. Agent (Mr. Louis Villanueva) was sent for a Drug test: and result were negative.
column169: As a result of this incident, Alliance Airlines will perform a recurrent training of Dangerous Goods handling awarenessto all warehouse personnel. All Supervisory staff are advised to monitor all agents who handles Dangerous Goods, and implement the safety proccedure.

column168: On 10/11/09 at approximately 0950 hours a Dana/Suttles tank trailer was in the process of unloading Tetrahydrofuran into an aboveground storage tank when the IMTT Operator noticed product dripping from the lower hose connection (nipple).  The operator immediately shut down the operation and placed a 5-gallon pail under the trailer to collect the dripping product.  The tanker, which was under pressure, was then depressurized and this eliminated the leaking.  The truck was transported to a location closer to the appropriate tank and resumed operation without requiring pressurization.  No further incident was reported.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident.  The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company and will address any mechanical or structural issues the truck or related components to prevent recurrences.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: This event occurred after driving made pickup from shipper. Driver strapped the drum against the wall of his trailer and proceeded to next stop. While in transit to next stop driver heard something fall over in his trailer and he stopped to investigate. He discovered that the drum had become unsecured from the strap and as a result it fell over in transit and hit a piece of equipment consequently puncturing the drum. The driver rolled the drum over to stop the leak and the repaired it with drum putty. Driver also used his onboard spill kit and contained and mitigated the spill with sorbents and placed them into a recovery container. Damaged drum was secured in trailer and brought to domiciled terminal awaiting final disposition.
column169: Driver needs to make sure that when using securement devices that they are properly utilized and attached to prevent relative motion of hazardous freight in transit.

Further investigation revealed that freight was loaded on top of this pail that was too heavy with no protective dunnage inbetween and as a result it partially crushed the top and closure of this pail contributing to the unintentional release.Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent material and placed into a recovery container as was the damaged pail.

A driver arrived at a shipper's location with the intention of accepting 2 X 55 gallon containers of a hazardous waste liquid (chromium) for transport to a fully licensed disposal facility.  Upon arrival, the driver intiated the loading process at which time he identified a small amount of material leaking from the bottom chime of the container.  The driver immediately placed the container on it side and retrieved an 85 gallon salvage drum carried upon his vehicle in the event of an emergency.  The driver placed the leaking container into the salvage drum and absorbed all free liquids with speedi dry.  The spill debris was collected and placed into the salvage drum.  Upon completion of the over packing operation, the driver secured the containers and proceeded to complete the loading operation.  Once the containers were loadied, the driver proceeded to transport the containers to the intended waste management facility.
column169: IN order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been re instructed to insure that each container is inspected before we initiate loading operations.  A thorough inspection will indeitify those containers that could present a problem during transportation.

column168: On 10/26/09 at approximately 1120 hours an Eastern Bulk Transporter tanker trailer was receiving a load of methanol.  At approximately 1500 gallons loaded the IMTT operator noticed methanol dripping at a weld joint near the back end of the tanker trailer.  The operator immediately stopped the operation and placed a 5-gallon pail under the trailer to collect the dripping product.  The trailer was then secured and moved to a designated containment area where the contents was off loaded to another tanker trailer.  The new trailer was tranported back to the loading rack and the operation resumed without incident.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident.  The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company and will address any mechanical or structural issues with the truck or related components to prevent recurrences.

Vacuum truck was parked on an incline, rear end up while loading.  Because the vacuum truck was not on level ground the float ball shutoff mechanism in the scrubber did not function and approximately 50 gallons of waste came out of the scrubber onto the ground, spill was contained by driver. Vacuum truck was moved to level ground and the 50 gallons was vacuumed up with the same tanker. Speedy dry was applied to absorb the remaining liquid and disposed of.

column168: According to information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading, one (1) 15-gallon drum was discovered damaged.  Wilson Trucking personnel placed the damaged drum into a metal recovery drum, to prevent leakage.  Due to the nature of the product involved, the product corroded the metal drum and leaked onto the dock at the facility.  A&D Environmental of High Point, North Carolina was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, the drum had been placed on cardboard, and was isolated on a pavement surface in the lot at the facility.  A&D Environmental neutralized the free product with the application of soda ash and kitty litter to the free liquid on the dock and pavement.  The spent soda ash, kitty litter, neutralized product, and cleanup debris were containerized into one (1) 85-gallon recovery drum.  The damaged 15-gallon drum was overpacked into one (1) 30-gallon overpack, pending disposal.  There were no soils or waters of the state affected or threatened by the release.  Two (2) recovery drums of waste were generated during cleanup.  One (1)85-gallon overpack w/cleanup debris and neutralized product, and one (1) 30-gallon drum w/the damaged drum.  Disposal will be coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be the result of a pinhole leak in the drum, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Wilson Trucking will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: During a tire check, driver noticed a small weep at the rear door of the vacuum box container. Upon closer inspection, it was determined that a piece of angle iron that is designed to act as a channel for the gasket when pressure is applied from closing, had a broken stitch weld. This broken weld allowed the angle iron to pull slightly from the container, which in turn released torque from the gasket, thus eliminating the integrity of the seal. The local New York DEC office was contacted and Clean Harbors was given permission to transfer the product to another vacuum box on site. A field service crew performed the transfer using the proper PPE. The laod transfer was conducted without incident and the damaged container was placed out of service pending repairs.
column169: At the time the load was nitially accepted for transportation, an inspection of the rear seal found no visual evidence of leaking or damage.  The driver did take appropriate action when he re-inspected his load and he has been reminded to insure that load checks are done at the prescribed frequency as this diligence can and in this case did reduce the potential for a more serious unintentional release.    The container involved was palced out of service pending repairs to the rear closure device.

column168: On October 20, 2009 at 1111 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Queensgate yard discovered UTLX68458, a loaded  tank car of Sodium Hydrosulfide, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2009-10-20-00091). Eagle Construction, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and could not find a leak. The following morning an odor was emanating again from the car. Veolia, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a defective vacuum relief valve (VRV). Contractor personnel removed the VRV from the car because the o-ring could not be replaced or repaired. A threaded plug was installed into the VRV nipple and the car was stenciled Do Not Load, Home Shop for Repair. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport once shipper obtained FRA movement approval. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code:458  NARRI: 5(5+3+1) X (2+0) = 90

column168: On 10/20/2009 at 1820 hrs., CSXT Hazardous Material managers were performing an inspection at the Big 4 yard in Russell, KY and found MWHX 1116, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Gases, releasing vapors from the sample line. The car was isolated in the rail yard and unsuccessful attempts were made to stop the leak. The shipper was notified of the incident via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-10-20-00201). Local authorities from Greenup County were also notified. The leak could not be fully stopped therefore a Midland capping kit was placed over the sample line to contain the vapors. FRA movement approval  #09100496 was granted allowing the car to be sent back to Mark West Hydrocarbons for unloading and repair.    This move required a special switch.   This incident will require a 7.1.   Cause Code: 511  NARRI:  2(5+5+0) X (2+0) = 40

column168: When driver was making a delivery, he noticed 3 drums shrink wrapped on a pallet and tied to the wall had shifted. The customer removed the pallet from the trailer onto the dock so the driver could resituate them on the pallet to reload. Our driver using a drum/barrel truck apparently punctured the bottom side edge of the drum with the tip of the barrel truck causing a leak.    These drums weighed 725 pounds each compared to the normal weight o 450 to 550 for a 55 gallon drum. This extreme weight may have played a part in making the drum hard to brake back with the barrel truck leading to the puncture.
column169: We will lookinto a better strapping system to be sure these heavy drum don't shift so they won't need to be resituate on the pallet. If a barrel truck is used on these drums, aded care will be taken to ensure they are not damaged.

column168: At this point in time we can only assume something happened on the customers tank.  It had a capacity of 11,800 gallons and ended up at 74% after the spill?  The overflow tube on the tank is set at 100% or the very top.  They have warning sensors that are supposed to go off at 90% and again at 95%.  The customer believes air pressure used during the delivery is what caused the spill to happen.  We agree in that spills can happen as a result of using air pressure, especially if the hoses go empty and air continues to feed through.  However in the past 30 years, every incident that has occurred as a result of continued air pressure at the end of a delivery, a small amount sprays up and hits the ceiling and 10-15 gallons is the spilled amount.  This is when the customer tank is near full.  This tank in question had quite a bit of headspace if it was only at 74% capacity.  Bubbling or bursting air inside the tank would have a hard time bursting 1000 gallons through the top.  This would have had to continue for quite some time!  The electronic chart on their tank supports the fact that we did not come close to overflowing the tank.  The pictures show where product was clearly overflowing from the tank.  That means the sensors and gauges inside must be off as the sensors never went off and the capacity should have had ample room to fit in the tank.  There is nothing associated to this incident that gives me any feeling we were the root cause on this.
column169: We are making the recommendation to the customer to have the electronic hardware in their tank checked.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported GATX 80141 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the manway closure during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was notified and immediately inspected GATX 80141. The responder reported seals were intact. The responder found all six manway securement bolts were not tool tight, but finger loose. Also, the manway gasket was inspected and appeared to be deteriorated with only a partial gasket seated in place. The responder removed the remnants of the old gasket and applied a new manway gasket and properly tool tightened the manway securement bolts. Response was concluded by 2300 hrs. CDT, 10/23/09. All spillage evaporated and no ground impact was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securemnet and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Liquid Valve
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported NATX 37686 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the top fitting area while in the railyard. NATX 37686 was cordoned off in the railyard. The local FD responded and initiated spill containment procedures using absorbent pads and a catch receptacle under the NATX 37686. BNSF contract responders and a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected NATX 37686. The responders reported that the leak source was from the liquid line valve. The 3 inch ball valve on the liquid line was partially open due to this valve's handle resting on the one inch vapor valve which prevented movement to full closure of the valve. Product was bypassing the liquid valve's closure plug. Internal pressure within the tank car was relieved via the vapor valve. Responders tightened the liquid valve to a position where the valve's handle could be fully closed. The closure plug was removed, cleaned, Teflon taped and reapplied to a tool tight condition. It was also noted that the vapor valve's closure plug was not applied and it too was cleaned, Teflon taped and applied to a tool tight condition. Securement was finalized by 1855 hrs, CDT, 10/06/09. Spillage within the valve housing area, on the tank shell and the ground impact areas were sprayed down with Microblaze followed by a water rinse from an onsite FD vehicle. Approximately 20 gallons of non-contaminated product captured in the catch receptacle was poured back into NATX 37686 via the manway. Intact seals removed were numbered BDWRR 0006174, 0006175 and then replaced with seals numbered SRS 000414,000415.   The side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification of NATX 37686 was completed in the year 2007 and next due in 2017.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

The spill occurred during off loading of a transformer from a flatbed trailer at the Veolia facility located in Phoenix, AZ.  Off loading was performed with a forklift and boom when the fork truck operator broke a side bushing causing a breach into the interior of the transformer. The transformer swayed during the lift, causing the transformer to contact the mast. The contact with the mast caused the side bushings to break, which caused a breach of the transformer carcass, releasing approximately 50-75 gallons of oil, up to the point of the breach. The breach was approximately 21 inches from the top of the transformer. The spill was contained to the immediate loading bay area and contcrete containment.  Oil was not released to the storm drains.
column169: Receiving personnel have been instructed on proper rigging of transformers for off loading. If the future,  crane services will be hired for the management and offloading of large transformers.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: On October 15, 2009 Landstar contacted ERTS to manage a leaking 55 gallon drum of a UN1263 at 9020 San Mateo Drive in Laredo, TX.  The drum had leaked approx 12 ounces of the product onto the top of the drum and the consignee would not accept the leaking drum.  ERTS contacted United States Environmental Services to coordinate a response for cleanup activities.    USES personnel responded to the scene and cleaned the leaked product and disposed of the contaminated materials properly.  USES personnel placed the leaking drum into an 85 gallon overpack.  Since the consignee would not accept the leaking drum, arrangements have been made for the leaking drum in the overpack to be shipped back to the shipper.

column168: On October 19, 2009 a Veolia ES Technical Solutions, LLC (Veolia) vehicle transporting hazardous wastes on the highway had to suddenly apply brakes in an effort to stop the vehicle as another truck suddenly pulled directly in front of the Veolia truck causing a load of drums on the Veolia truck to shift in the forward direction towards the nose of the vehicle. The sliding motion caused these drums to move and hit against the row of drums all the way in the front of the truck.    This impact caused one of the lids of a 55-gallon drum containing paint related material to pop off and create a leak inside the trailer. Upon noticing through his mirrors that the liquid was dripping out of the vehicle the driver pulled along the side of the freeway and started to take appropriate remedial actions including, berming, setting up of triangles, containment etc. The driver also called for help at the same time. A response crew arrived on scene. The spill was mainly contained within the trailer and is estimated to be approximately 5 gallons. There was some liquid which hit the ground which was also remediated by the response crew.     Upon containing of the release and securing of the load the vehicle, was taken back to the Veolia facility.
column169: The load was secured using a ratchet style load bar which was not able to hold the load as the shift occurred due to the sudden braking of the vehicle. In this instance a load bar that would have connected into the vehicle tracks inside the trailer designed for this purpose would have been a better choice.  Veolia will retrain employees on proper selection of load securement devices, proper loading & securing requirements as well as defensive driving.

column168: On 10/23/09 at 2115 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Gentilly Yard in New Orleans, LA., discovered GATX300461, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquids, N.O.S., crude sulfate turpentine, leaking from the manway area. The car was isolated and the shipper, Boise Cascade LLC, Louisiana state police and the local fire department were notified. (CHEMTREC Report # 2009102300195). United States Environmental Services, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found one manway bolt in the off position, two other manway bolts were less than tool tight, the vapor line secondary securement plug was less than tool tight and the protective cover for the valves was not pinned and secured. The issues identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Berry Chanceey at 251-589-4026. Contractor personnel fixed the problems and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60
column169: CSX Hazardous Materials Manager, Chris Machenberg, spoke with Adam Hoffman, 337-396-9318, at Boise Cascade LLC, to discuss a meeting at the shippers facility. Chris Machenberg met with Adam Hoffman and other members of Boise Cascade at the facility where the car was loaded on 10/27/2009 to discuss loading procedures. Check lists were examined and suggestions were made to better the process they were using. The AAR safety video was supplied to the shipper on loading and unloading tank cars.

column168: A BNSF road switch crew reported UTLX 211064 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the top fitting area of this tank car while it was in the railyard. BNSF operating and mechanical responders inspected UTLX 211064 finding the leak source at the 165 psi pressure relief device (PRD) which appeared not to be reclosing. Product spillage on the tank shell was evaporating. UTLX 211064 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting repair. The shipper requested a tank car mobile repair service provider to inspect and repair UTLX 211064, but the repair provider would not perform repair work on a loaded tank car of flammable liquid.  The shipper then arranged for UTLX 211064 to be off loaded with the product transferred to trucks and this was accomplished on 10/14/2009 without further incident. The shipper then arranged for a suitable replacement PRD to be sent and installed on UTLX 211064.   On 10/27/2009, a BNSF contractor removed the failed PRD (UTC serial number 46421) which had a broken stem and was missing the spring, follower and associated nut hardware. These missing items were inside the tank and retrieved by the contract responders. The replacement PRD (a 75 psi Midland PRD) was installed and properly secured and verified by a Union Tank Car (UTC) representative overseeing this repair work. UTLX 211064 was scheduled to be moved to an UTC repair facility for pressure testing under FRA movement approval FRA-09100477 (Revised).

column168: A 275 gallon tote of Sodium Hypochlorite was loaded on a flatbed trailer for transport. The tote was taller than the side rails on the trailer. A "load binding" strap was around the mid portion of the tote to prevent sliding or over turning.Driver was leaving a parking lot making a sharp turn onto the highway. The elevation of the parking lot and roadway were uneven.The combination of the turn and uneven elevation caused the trailer to "twist or flex".This created stress on the tote at the strapped area of the tote tank. This stress caused the tote to fail and split diagonally across one sideThe driver immediately called 911 and his supervisor to report the incident. Emergency responders arrived at the scene in a matter on minutes. A ditch along the highway was dammed up. The responders used water to dilute the Sodium Hypochlorite to neutral PH.An environmental service was called to the scene to vacuum up the diluted material for proper disposal.
column169: Transportation of totes of this particular type or design should be limited to a box truck, box trailer or flat bed with siderails or walls as tall as the tote.Totes should be designed so that the structural frame extends beyond the diameter of the "tank" all the way around to protect the "tank".Totes should have accommodations for attaching straps or chains to them to prevent movement during transportation.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading, one (1) 55-gallon drum was punctured by a forklift.  Approximately 40 gallons of free product were released to the concrete surface at the facility.  The Port Authority responded to assess the site, building was evacuated, as a precautionary measure.  Absorbent material was applied to contain the free product.  Environmental Products & Services of Orangeburg, New York responded to perform the cleanup.  Environmental Products & Services applied additional absorbent material to the remaining free liquid.  The spent absorbents were containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drums.  The damaged drum was overpacked into one (1) 85-gallon drum.  Drums were taken from the site, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.

Cleanup was performed by DB Schenker, Inc. employee's Juanita Arreola and Juan Miguel.  The cleanup was performed using gloves, goggles, apron, respirator and absorbent materials.  The contaminated absorbent materials, cleanup material and damaged drum were placed into an over-pack drum.  The over-pack drum was placed into the OS&D bay pending further instructions.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, DB Schenker, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: The driver had hooked a drop hose for delivery and had product flowing from the tank.    He next went to remove another drop hose from the hose tube, in so doing the far end of the hose as it came out of the hose tube dropped down on the other drop hose that was hooked and had product flowing.     At this point the gravity coupler came dislodged from the tank units loading head.  This allowed product to flow for 3 seconds until the driver closed the delivery valve.  The interior lip on the gravity coupler was not machined as deep on this gravity coupler as the others.  This did not make for a solid connection.  Thus when lightly stuck by another drop hose the coupler came loose.
column169: Gravity Coupler was replaced

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Misaligned Material, Component, or Device
column168: A FRA Rail Safety Inspector (Hazardous Materials) inspecting a BNSF outbound train consist in the railyard discovered and reported PPRX 28540 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product at the valve housing area atop this tank car. During a joint FRA/BNSF mechanical inspection, intact seal numbered 583636 was removed to inspect the valves under the valve housing cover. Inspection revealed that all valves were in the closed position and their corresponding closure plugs tool tight. Product was bypassing the 3 inch liquid valve's closure plug. PPRX 28540 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. BNSF contract responders were called to remedy the product leak. The contract responders opened the vapor valve to reduce internal pressure within PPRX 28540 and also performed air monitoring during this process. The liquid valve was then inspected and found closed with its closure plug tool tight. The plug was removed and no thread sealant was observed on the threaded portion of this plug. No product was observed in the open valve orifice after the plug was removed. The Teflon seal atop the ball valve appeared not fully seated with approximately one inch circumference of this seal out of position.  The responders reseated this seal and the valve was cycled open/closed to ensure the seal remained properly seated. Thread sealant was applied to the closure plug's threaded area, the plug placed into position and tool tightened. Spillage around the valve housing and on the tank shell was wiped. Responders monitored PPRX 28540 afterwards for approximately two hours with no further product release evident. The valve housing cover was closed, secured and sealed with seal numbered 5116. Response was concluded by 1900 hrs. MDT, 10/19/2009.  PPRX 28540's side specification stencil indicated that its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2006 and next due in 2016.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Diesel tank capacity at receiving location is 1000 gallons. Receiving location's storeroom personnel incorrectly gauged tank and ordered 700 gallons. Driver of bulk delivery truck had unloaded 578 gallons of diesel when diesel came out the vent off the top of the tank. Driver immediately noticed the overfill and quickly shut off his pump. Driver notified storeroom personnel and began placing absorbent pads on the spill. Diesel primarily entered the tank secondary containment area, although a very small amount was blown onto the adjacent asphalt. Receiving location contacted a spill clean up contractor to clean and decontaminate the containment area, the tank, and the adjacent asphalt. It was estimated that less than 1/2 gallon of diesel was spilled due to the overfilling of the receiving facility's tank.The primary cause of the failure was due to a gauging error by the receiving facility storeroom personnel. More diesel was ordered than available tank capacity.
column169: Storeroom personnel have come up with an action plan to prevent reoccurrence. The following are the key components of this action plan. 1. Use of a fuel log to double check gauging calculations 2. Verify gauging stick reaches bottom of tank 3. Require fuel vendor to gauge tank before delivery. Install fill valve locks to ensure that vendor can not off-load without storekeeper knowledge. Storekeeper to witness vendor gauging and compare readings. Storekeeper to post strapping charts on or near tank. 4. Use of fuel off-loading checklists.

column168: A BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED PROX 98362 (DOT 112J340W TANK CAR) EMANATING A PRODUCT ODOR WHILE THIS TANK CAR WAS IN THE BOWL TRACKS IN THE CLASSIFICATION YARD.  PROX 98362 WAS CAREFULLY MOVED AND ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD.  BNSF OPERATING PERSONNEL NOTIFIED A NEARBY BNSF CONTACT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER TO INSPECT PROX 98362.  THE RESPONDER'S INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THAT THE SEAL AT THE VALVE HOUSING COVER WAS INTACT. THE B END LIQUID VALVE WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM ITS CLOSURE PLUG.  THE CLOSURE PLUG WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT (FINDER LOOSE) AND THE LIQUID VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN.  THIS VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE CLOSURE PLUG TOOL TIGHTENED, ENDING PRODUCT DRIPS BY 0330 HRS. CDT, 10/07/09.  THE A-END LIQUID VALVE'S CLOSURE PLUG WAS ALSO FOUND FINGER LOOSE AND IT WAS TOOL TIGHTENED.  THE PRODUCT SPILLAGE IN THE VALVE HOUSING WAS ESTIMATED AS SEVERAL OUNCES WHICH READLY EVAPORATED.  NO GROUND IMPACT WAS EVIDENT.  THE VALVE HOUSING COVER WAS RESEALED WITH A BNSF SEAL.  PROX 98362'S SPECIFICATION STENCIL INDICATED THAT ITS LAST TANK QUALIFICATION WAS COMPLETED IN THE YEAR 2000 AND NEXXT DUE IN 2010.

column168: TILX 251032 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car), a cross-border shipment that originated in Mexico, was reported by a BNSF switchman leaking product from its top fitting area during movement in the railyard. Movement of TILX 251032 was stopped. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was then notified to inspect TILX 251032. The responder reported finding all eight (8) manway securement bolts less than tool tight (finger loose),The manway gasket was checked with no issues noted. The responder properly tool tightened all manway securement bolts prior to Noon CDT,10/03/2009. One of the two seals intact at the manway closure numbered INT 36203 was replaced by seal numbered BNSF 002417. All spillage evaporated. No further product release from TILX 251032 was observed from subsequent movements in the railyard.

column168: Transport was traveling east on Hwy 518 just east of Millport, OH when the driver was attempting to turn south on Hwy 164. This intersection is a yield no stop is required if traffic is clear. The transport was traveling at 18 mph when the wheels left the road which was too fast for this particular turn. The transport rolled onto it's side in the ditch on the east side of Hwy 164. Product was released from the vent and dome lid. Local emergency responders dug a hole at each end of the transport which limited the travel of product and allowed the product to be recovered from the holes. I will file a followup report when I have the total costs of product lost, carrier damage, and response costs.

column168: On October 5, 2009, a Ward Trucking tractor-trailer was involved in an incident that caused the release of UN1564 Barium Acetate inside the trailer.  It was estimated that 20-30 gallons of product were released from a tear in one of the packages.  Northridge Group Environmental responded to the incident on October 6, 2009.  They freight was unloaded from the trailer and re-secured to prevent a secondary release.  The trailer was then swept clean and the freight was decontaminated.  All waste was collected and transported off site for disposal.

A van trailer containing hazardous was enroute from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor's in-transit storage facility to consolidate less than truck load quantities onto a single vehicle for continued transportation.  During the transfer operation, a 55 gallon polyehtylene container was found to have developed a crack on the bottom of the container allowing material to be released to the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel immediately placed the container upside down to stop the release.  Assistance was then obtained and, using appropriate personal protective equipment, the container was placed into a suitable salvage drum along with all absorbent material used to collect the material that was released.  Once the response activities were finalized, the completed container was placed onto the vehicle and sent for disposal at the intended waste management facility.
column169: An inspection of the damaged container indicated that it showed signs of aging which is believed to have resulted in the container becoming brittle.  The individuals responsible for accepting the container for transportation along with the loading personnel have been re-intstructed to conduct a thorough inspection of every container and to take appropriate actions should a container show signs of reduced structural integrity.

column168: A box truck containing hazardous waste was in the process of being received at the intended waste management facility.  During the receiving process it was identified that a small amount of material was leaking from the front of the cargo compartment. Facility personnel were alerted and an emergency response team was assembled.  Using appropriate personal protective equipment, facility personnel entered the trailer and determined that a 55 gallon container had developed a leak from the top closure of the container.  Further inspection identified that the gasket was cracked allowing the material to escape down the side of the container.  Facility personnel replaced the defective gasket and sealed the container.  The released material was collected with a suitable absorbent material and this clean-up debris was containerized pending proper disposal at the intended waste management facility.    MULTIPLE REPORT  A box truck containing hazardous waste was in the process of being received at the intended waste management facility.  During the receiving process it was identified that a small amount of material was leaking from the front of the cargo compartment. Facility personnel were alerted and an emergency response team was assembled.  Using appropriate personal protective equipment, facility personnel entered the trailer and determined that a 55 gallon container had developed a small leak at the bottom seam of the drum.  Facility personnel placed the damaged container into a suitable salvage drum and absorbed all free liquid with a suitable absorbent material.  This material was collected and placed into the salvage drum which was then disposed at the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the containers were accepted for transportation, the containers were inspected and no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. column168: Associate punctured freight with forklift blades while loading / unloading causing product to leak.  All product was absorbed with oil dry and placed into a salvage drum and was handled according to all local, state, and federal regulations.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Driver, as he made a required haz-mat railroad crossing stop, saw liquid splash on the ground from under the trailer. When he got out to look, he saw product coming from the front vent valve piping. Upon closer inspection he realized the vent valve, located at the top front of the trailer, was in the open position. The trailers are equiped with interlocking brake valves that are designed to hold the trailer brakes in the locked position when the vent valve is in the open position. The brake interlock valve did not lock the brakes when the vent valve failed. The driver notified his supervisor of the incident and a cleanup crew was dispatched to the scene along with safety department personel to neutralize the sulfuric Acid and clean up.
column169: All equipment so equipped have been checked to verfy the vent valves are in proper operating condition and the brake interlock systems do work. Drivers have been made aware that an additional time needs to be utilized in their inspections of these valve systems to assure they are operational.

column168: RESPONDED TO LEAKING PACKAGE.  USED THE DECISION TREE WHICH LED ME TO THE NON-FLAMMABLE GAS RESPONSE SHEET.  USED PPE AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL ACCORDING TO THE RESPONSE SHEET.  PROCESSED THRU THE DMP.  LOCKING PIN ON FIRE EXTINGUISHER CAME LOOSE DURING SHIPMENT CAUSING THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO RELEASE CONTENTS.
A LEAKING HAZMAT WAS FOUND AT BAY 31.UPON INSPECTION PACKAGE HAD BEEN CRUSHED. ONE OF THREE PLASTIC BOTTLES WAS CRUSHED,CONTAMINATING THE OTHER TWO. PEANUTS WERE USED FOR PACKING.

RESPONDED TO OB-8 BAY-1058, WHERE THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS FOR A FLAMMABLE LIQUID SPILL WAS USED. BOOTS, APRON, GOGGLES, CHEMICAL RESISTANT SLEEVES AND GLOVES (LATEX AND NITRILE.) THE SPILL APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED WHEN DIVERTED INTO BAY-1058 IN OB-8. WE ASSUME THE GLASS CYLINDER CRACKED ON IMPACT, SINCE THE SHOOT AND ROLLERS WERE SOILED. THE PACKAGE WAS LOADED ON THE BOTTOM LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER. THERE WAS A PARTIAL EVACUATION OF OUTBOUND FREIGHT FOR ABOUT 15 MINUTES. ABOUT 30 EMPLOYEES WERE AFFECTED DURING THE EVACUATION. column168: The shipment was unloaded from trailer 86493 and checker Sylvester Bryant noticed wetness behind the shrinkwrap.  We proceeded to place the whole shipment on empty trailer 80707 to isolate it and sent the trailer to the yard.  The labels are all damp on one drum and there is wetness under the cap of   that same drum and one other.  There is no residue on the floor of the trailer it came off and there is not a constant drip or a drip at all.  Some of the solution has dried and somewhat crystalized on the bottom edge of the cap.

Our employee was unloading 2 Rail cars on our siding which is located at the service unit.  The siding is on a slight hill. Two hoses were hooked up to the two cars.  The Rail car on the end started rolling down the track over the chock blocks ripping the hoses.  The release was instant and small coming from the ripped hoses and hard pipe between the back checks and the hose.
column169: Our management met with a team of Rail Road representatives.  The brakes looked as though they may have been tampered with.  Vandalism is believed to be the cause of the incident. It has been recommended to use a different style of chock block that locks.

column168: Driver of the truck was attempting to make a U-turn and a pin on the pup trailer broke causing the pup trailer to overturn. Fuel was leaking from the top of the tank at the fill cap. RRT 5 responded and attempted to clamp off the cap to stop the leak. That did not work and found out later that a small rock had gotten jammed in the cap and wouldn't let the clamp work. The spill caused the evacuation of a small gas station, a small hotel, a school and five residences in the area. Conrad & Bischoff had another truck arrive to off load the fuel on the pup trailer and and called a wrecker to the scene to upright the trailer.

THE SEAMS ON THE PACKAGING MUST BE ABLE TO HOLD LIQUID WITHOUT LEAKING OUT.  THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND/OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION.  IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE.  TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED.  DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column168: Container MHUU 634732 was noted leaking a green liquid from the rear doors.  Inspection noted 22 packages, super sacks, containing Ferrous Sulfate.  No placards or markings were observed on the exterior of the container.  The super sacks appear to have been loaded during inclimate weather as the bags were wet. Moisture wicked through the super sack material into the solid product, then leached back out of the super sack, carrying residue product.  The super sacks were encapsulated in large heavy duty poly bags to contain any further leakage.  The flooring of the container was cleaned of the residue, and the lading placed back into the original container for movement onto the consignee. column168: On 10-27-09 at approx. 17:30, driver from Roland J. Robert Distr. was delivering off-road diesel fuel into CN Railroad Locomotive #2459 which was located on Zen-Noh Grain facility in Convent, LA.  Driver indicated that he had delivered most of the fuel into locomotive when fuel came out of fill tube and he turned off nozzle.  Driver removed absorbent pads from truck and placed them on top of fuel that was on part of rail bed and on concrete ditch.  Driver said that he had not noticed any other fuel on the ground and proceeded to notify one of employees of the spill and he thought was taken care of.  At approx. 18:00 one of ZGC employees noticed fuel on the far side of the trench & notified his supervisors.  The supervisors notified CNIC Railroad Jason Belamy who contacted Chris Lanoue of CN Railroad who arrived at location 21:00.  Also Robert Distr.'s personnel were notified and driver was immediately sent back to location with more pads to further assess the situation.  Sales rep for Robert notified Gayle Robert who was in route and arrived at location at approx 21:30. He met with CN and Zen-Noh personnel and asked that Zen-Noh report the incident, and they immediately called at 22:03 and reported the incident (Incident #09-05933), and proceeded to take steps for spill prevention:  put dirt into ditch to stop product form going off the immediate area; 7-8 absorbent booms were placed wherever there was any trace of fuel; bundle of absorbent pads were dispersed where needed.  Robert dispatched two of his men to assist in making sure that everything visible was absorbed by pads or booms and placed into metal containers.  The Robert employees arrived back at 8:00 next morning to further assist in cleaning and clearing anything needed. Further observations were made and all seems to be clean with no sheen or trace of fuel.  Contaminated soil and rags will be disposed of properly and site will be monitored by Zen-Noh and further information will be supplied as everything is completed.

OUR DRIVERS ARE TRAINED TO ALWAYS CHECK FOR THE DRUMS AND THEIR INTEGRITY, ENSURE THE DRUM AND VESSEL COUNTS ARE CORRECT, AND ENSURE THAT THE HAZ WASTE LOAD IS SECURED APPROPRIATELY. column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Odors were reported emitting from IM Tank CCRU 196106 while being loading onto an eastbound train on track 805, ICTF Intermodal Facility.  The IM Tank was moved to an isolated area of the Intermodal Facility and secured pending inspection.  Odors were apparent within 15-20 feet down wind of the IM Tank.  Top inspection determined the vapor release was coming from the top forward area of the IM Tank where the (2) two dual combination pressure relief valves were located.  Hoyer, the tank owner, arranged to have SRS, their contracted hazardous material response contractor, fly in and remediate the leak.  Closer inspection by SRS developed the (4) four bolts that secure the PRV flange to the tank, were loose on the right side PRV, allowing vapors to escape.  The (4) bolts were properly secured, which stopped the leak.  The adjacent PRV was inspected and found to be intact.  The rear vapor and liquid lines were inspected and found the secondary (4) four bolt flange on the vapor valve, and the secondary (4) four bolt flange on the liquid line were less than tool tight.  There were no leaks noted as the in line valves were closed.  Both flanges were properly secured
column169: Proper inspection and securement prior to transport.

Driver was doing his pretrip and noticed a hydraulic oil leak from the hydraulic pump.  Mechanic was called to repair pump.  They then noticed product dripping from the skin of the trailer.  Product was transferred into a relief trailer to complete delivery.

Due to roll-over accident, the trailer dome lid was torn off of trailer allowing release of product. All of the product released was contained in the road side ditch. The liquid material was immediately removed and the contaminated soil was excavated. All recovered material was sent off for disposal. The area was backfilled and overseeded per Texas DOT Requirements.

column168: Driver was traveling approx. 4.5 miles on a straight section of NM SR 39. Approx. 3.2 miles north of Mosquero, NM the road made an approx. 45 degree curve to the southwest. At the point where the curve initiated the driver failed to negotiate the curve and began to leave the roadway. The driver then corrected to attempt a correction back onto the roadway. At that point due to 1) severity of turn 2) no shoulder on roadway 3) incline of embankment the tractor and trailer rolled onto the passenger side. Upon crossing a drainage culvert at a cross street the rear compartment of the trailer shell was compromised by an approx 3' tear. The tractor and trailer continued another 180 degree roll and came to rest on the driver side. The dome lids on the intact compartments were releasing small amounts of material due to the positon at which the trailer was at rest. Raton, NM HazMat response unit arrived on seen and closed the roadway and secured the dome lids to prevent further leakage. At that point all material release was stopped approx 2 hours after initial accident. An empty tanker was dispatched from Amarillo, TX and the remaining material was transferred to the empty unit for transport back to Amarillo, Texas. Rivas Environmental Service of Amarillo, TX was contracted to remediate the site. Remediation by rivas continues under the direction of the New Mexico Department of Environmental Quality and the New Mexico Department of Transportation.
column169: Continue to stress, in all safety meetings, the critical need to adjust speed appropriately to road and weather conditions.

column168: ON OR ABOUT OCTOBER 13, 2009 IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A MARATHON 28695 TYPE CA-154-2 BATTERY WAS SHIPPED TO A VENDOR AND NOT IDENTIFIED AS HAZMAT.  THE BATTERY WAS SHIPPED IN AN UNAPPROVED SHIPPING CONTAINER THAT WAS THE INCORRECT TYPE AND SIZE.  THE BATTERY WAS LAID ON ITS SIDE DUE TO ITS HEIGHT, AND NO SECURE MEANS OF PACKING ALLOWED IT TO MOVE FREELY IN THE BOX.  (SEE THE PHOTOGRAPHS)  THE VENDOR REPORTED THAT UPON OPENING THE BOX THEY FOUND THE BATTERY ON ITS SIDE AND THE METALLIC LINKS WERE ALLOWED TO MAKE CONTACT WITH 2 METALLIC SCREWS THAT HELD THE RETAINING STRAP.
