column168: Driver arrived at delivery location at approximately 0700 am and set up for delivery of two grades of gasoline; (ElO / 87 Octane Gasoline w/10% ethanol & E-10 / 93 Octane Gasoline w/ ethanol). Driver had completed connections from trailer outlet line valve to our product hose and tank connection fitting onto customer tank connection for the 87 octane gasoline and started product flow. Driver then completed connections from trailer outlet line valve to our product hose and tank connection fitting onto customer tank connections for the 93 octane gasoline and started product flow. Driver reports that he started to turn to his right (toward the front of our transport unit); heard a noise and turned his head back and noticed 6” x 4” adapter fitting for the 93 octane gasoline, had come loose from the trailer outlet product line and that gasoline (93 octane) was spilling from trailer outlet line and the 4” product hose, that had the 6” x4” adapter connected to it, had struck the ground (adapter fitting came loose from the connection to the trailer outlet piping). Driver then shut (closed) the valve compartment door of the trailer; which by doing so closed the belly valve of the trailer. Driver then picked up the product hose, which had fallen to the ground, and reconnected the hose (with the 6” x4” adapter back to the 6” outlet line of the trailer for the 93 octane gasoline. Driver used spill pads from our transport unit supply and spread in area to assist in controlling flow of the gasoline that had spilled that was traveling down a slight slope of the parking lot away from the unloading area. Driver then advised store personnel of the spill situation and the need for response to the spill situation. Local fire department, police department as well as the local street department which did place sand/absorbent materials onto the area that was impacted by the spilled gasoline. During the response, a representative of the WVDEP UST Division was enroute to his office for workday and also stopped and responded to the spill situation. Fire Department felt the spill incident had been contained and advised would respond later in day to sweep up and remove the gasoline impacted absorbent materials. Representative with the WVDEP advised facility owner to proceed with appropriate notifications and to have a certified environmental clean —up company respond to remediate the situation. WVDEP representative also advised the responding environmental remediation company to take directed samples from the location for remedial review. Environmental company (Ryan’s Environmental) completed all surface clean-up and performance of the taking of samples as directed the same day of the spill event). Pos the initial containment and clean-up of the unloading area our driver completed the delivery process of the gasoline products (both the 87 octane and the 93 octane); stick readings were taken, in the presence if the facility owner and the representative of the WVDEP, post the
column169: Post incident interview with driver reflected: Driver claims the 6” x 4” Adapter fitting that connects on the 6” side to the trailer product outlet line and on the 4” side to the product hose that runs from our trailer connection to the customer tank connection came loose at the 6” side that connects to the trailer product outlet pipe connection. This fitting has Cam-Lock fasteners on both the 6” side and the 4” side. Driver stated that the 6”x4” adapter fitting appeared to be “tight” as he did not observe any appearance of the cam-lock ears not being in the closed/tightened position, nor did he detect any looseness of the fitting when he made connect ion of the product hose to the adapter fitting in preparation for the unloading of product from the trailer.   Post the incident the 6” x 4” adapter fitting, the trailer compartment product line outlet fitting and the 4” product hose cam lock fittings were all checked and no observable defects were noted. Proper connections, between and to each component, were made using the same components and it was found the components made tight and secure connections between all parts. All of the involved components have returned/continued in service and noted to be operating property.   Best assumption is that either the cam lock fittings (ears) had vibrated loose at some point prior to the driver making the hook-up connections of which the driver did not make note of the condition when he made his component connections prior to unloading or that the driver had not properly secured a seated/ tight position of one, or both, of the cam lock ears when he connected the 6” side of the 6” x4” adapter fitting to the trailer product outlet line fitting and as a result the connection became disengaged. Proper loading and unloading procedures are included in our classroom and field training with a driver trainer for all hired driver employees. Each driver employee receives a copy of our in- depth Driver Training Manual. We have ongoing quarterly safety and operational meetings with all of our driver personnel and will again target discussion and presentation of proper loading/unloading procedures to include specific reference to this particular incident in our next set of quarterly safety meetings and detail the proper procedures associated to component connections for both the loading and unloading process and how best to avoid this type of situation occurring. As noted, we have quarterly safety meetings and had just completed a week prior to this event our most recent quarterly safety meetings that as part of the covered topics included specific instruction on fitting and connection integrity at our customer delivery locations. As noted, we will again specifically target this topic in our next set of quarterly meetings and stress that driver employee observation and inspection of proper component connection is vital to avoid a situation such as this occurring.

column168: On Monday, October 12, 2009, at 1425 hours EST, Ms. Shara Lindsay from Quality Carriers Sky Tank contacted American Compliance Technologies, Inc. (A•C•T) Project Manager, Mr. Wayne Koszegi, CHMM to request assistance with a spill of Alkyd Resin.  The spill occurred at an EPS Drop Yard located at 231 Oak Ridge Drive in Hagerstown, Maryland. Ms. Lindsay advised that tanker #7287 developed a leak and released an estimated <10 gallons of product onto the sides of the tanker and soil parking area of the drop yard. No stormwater drains were in the area of the spill. No reporting was required as this spill was below the reportable quantity.  Additionally, Mr. John Bentley from the Washington County Emergency Management Agency was on site.       Upon arrival at the site, our response team advised that the resin had run down both sides of the tanker and a small amount had impacted the ground as shown in Figure 2 of the Maps and Photographs section of this report.  A•C•T emailed the MSDS to our response team, and the A•C•T project manager reviewed all safety measures required to clean this tanker. At the time of our response teams arrival there were no active leaks observed.    Our response team began the cleanup process by applying granular sorbents to the spilled material located on the parking area. After initial attempts to clean the tanker with MEK soaked rags were unsuccessfully, our response team switched to mineral spirits, which worked well.  During the cleanup operations the local fire department returned to the site and advised that there was product impacting a railroad crossing and the roadway leading to the drop yard and that cars are driving through the product.  Our response investigated the area.  No pooling was found at the railroad crossing.  A small amount of the resin was found on the roadway, but it was hardened and would not cause any problems.      On Tuesday, October 13, 2009 our response team returned to site to continue the clean-up process.  They reported that additional product had run down the sides of the tanker.  Apparently this was product that pooled on the top of the tanker that our response team was unable to see due to darkness the night before.  Our response team then began hand scraping the resin off the tanker. Our response team continued to clean the tanker until it became too dark to operate safely.  They will have to return for a third day to complete the cleanup.  Quality Carriers was undated and approved a third day of operations.    On Wednesday, October 14, 2009 our response team returned to the site to complete cleanup operations.  The final amount of resin on the sides of the trailer was scraped off and the tanker was wiped down with mineral spirits.  There was an area on the top of the tanker (under the catwalk) that was inaccessible, which did contain some hardened resin material.  All drummed waste was staged on site for future disposal.    WASTE DISPOSAL    All waste profiling and disposal was handled by

column168: On Thursday, October 8, 2009, at 1908 hours EST, Ms. Sue LeBlanc, from Quality Carriers Sky Tank contacted American Compliance Technologies, Inc. (A•C•T) Nationwide Project Manager, Mr. Gary L. Weiss to request assistance with a spill of Jeffamine D 2000 a Polyoxypropylenediamine Liquid (UN 2735). The spill occurred at a Pilot Truck Stop located at 259 Cherry Blossom Blvd. in Georgetown, Kentucky. Ms. LeBlanc advised that Mr. Mark Triman, the Quality Carriers driver, reported that his tanker was leaking product from the dome assembly.  A•C•T Project manager requested that Mr. Timan place a bucket under the leak and scrape some soil to build a dam to contain the spill and minimize the impact on the ground. Mr. Jack Donovan from the Scott County Emergency Management Agency was on site and advised that he notified KY-DEC and that the leak had been stopped.       Upon arrival at the site, our response team advised that the Scott County Fire Department was still inspecting the tanker.  Once the fire department completed their inspection they allowed our response team to enter the “hot zone”.  Our response team inspected the dome assembly area of the tanker and observed no active leaking.  The truck driver was asked to rock the truck back and forth a few times to make sure that the leak had stopped.  Our response team observed that there was still a leak in the dome assembly when the truck was rocked. The leak was isolated to a pressure release valve.  Sky Tank was contacted any advised that they would need a repair contractor to respond.     Our response team began the cleanup process by wiping down the exterior of the tanker where the product ran down.  All the wipe cloths were placed into a 30-gallon drum along with the absorbent media that the fire department had applied to solidify the product.    WASTE DISPOSAL    As a result of the response activities, one (1) 30-gallon drum of waste was generated.  After consulting with Mr. Rob Smale of Quality Distribution, a waste profile was developed. Upon profile approval, the waste was manifested and transported to Klor Kleen located in Cincinnati, Ohio for disposal.

At 1920 hours on Wednesday, October 7, 2009, Ms. Sue LeBlanc from Quality Distribution’s Sky Tank Hot Line notified A•C•T that tractor-tanker #30806 located at 13443 Dale Wood Drive in Baldwin Park, California developed a leak of Losurf 300 D, a Class III, UN1993 Hazardous Material.  Less than 20 gallons of product leaked out onto the highway.  The Las Angles County Fire Department (LACoFD) was on scene.  ACT Project Manager; Mr. Gary L. Weiss contacted Captain Wilson of the LACoFD to get further information on the incident.  Captain Wilson advised to standby on any cleanup response until the Hazardous Material Team (HMT) from the fire department inspects the site.    Mr. Weiss spoke to Hazardous Material Specialist Ishmael Gonzalez from the LACoFD HMT, Mr. Gonzalez reported that the California Department of Transportation (Caltrans) was cleaning up the roadway with sand and no private cleanup contractor would be needed.  Additionally, Mr. Gonzalez advised that there may be some damage in the dome lid area, but at this time no action is required.  The California Highway Patrol (CHP) conducted a complete vehicle inspection on the truck and tanker and advised Sky Tank personnel of the status of the tanker and any required service that would need to be performed.

column168: At approximately 0515am driver of our transport truck began to experience what is commonly refered to in the emulsion industry as a boil over which is caused by retained moisture in the trailer prior to loading the elevated temperature petroleum. At that time the driver moved to the shoulder of the road to minimize potential property and injury to motorists traveling the interstate.  The elevated temperature oil caused the moisture to expand at a rate greater than tank vents can exhaust, causing a release of the material under pressure thru the dome lid.  When this situation occurs there is little to be done but protect people and property from damage.  Once the pressure was released the trailer maintained its integrity and no further product was lost.  The release of pressure and material lasted approximately 2 minutes.
column169: We are monitoring the drying out of trailers more closely to ensure all moister is removed.  This incident is now part of our training.

column169: After further investigation by IMTT it was determined that a section of the product hose was deteriorated and caused the leak. At 8:16 today, Operations Supervisor Doug Short came to my office to report trailer # v6Ols had arrived from LAX and there was smoke coming out of the rear of the trailer door and a lIquid was leaking on the ground. He had the Mnifest with the shipments and the description 01 the one hazardous material on bill # 10843006 from Flo Kern that was on the trailer. I told the commander on duty I would be the point of contact. He wanted to do a quick walk through the building with me to be sure everyone was out. When that was completed we shut the gates. I then called Rita In Oakland and advised her we were being evacuated, and would advise when we were let back in. Trade had also notified Sherri in Reno. Once here the emergency services determined that they could not isolate the cause of the odor and checked out the employees that were unloading the aircraft.  The employees were cleard by EMS and offered to take them to the hospital for further checking which all three refused and signed documents stating such.  Later, all three went to a local first aid service, were looked at, released and were present at work the next day.    Our own investigation searching further revealed a wrapped tote with a strong odor of gasoline eminating from it.  After removing the plastic wrap and the contents, on the bottom of the tote was found a one gallon, red plastic, non-specification jerrican tipped over having leaking over half the contents in the bottom of the tote.

column168: THIS UNDECLARED PAINT SPILLED IN THE AFT BULK OF THE AIRCRAFT. THE PAINT CANS WERE MARKED DOT FLAMMABLE LIQUID PACKING GROUP II. I CONTACTED THE SHIPPER WHO WAS NOT AWARE OF HAZMAT SHIPPING REQUIREMENTS. THEY SENT ME AN MSDS THAT SHOWED UN1263 PGIII. SO THE PG IS NOT CERTAIN. LORI LUSCHER OF THE FAA IN SEATTLE WAS CONTACTED AT 1:30 ON NOV 2.
column169: I SPOKE TO THE SHIPPER AND EXPLAINED THEY MUST NOT SHIP ANY MORE FLAMMABLE PAINT UNTIL THEY ARE TRAINED. THEY SAID THEY HAVE SHIPPED THIS 6 OR 8 TIMES IN THE PAST. ACTUAL NAME OF THE COMPANY IS ROBINSON FANS  ALTHOUGH THE SHIPPER NAME (MS. SPRIK) ON THE AIRBIL WAS THE LADY WHO DID THE AIRBILL BUT SHE DID NOT PACKAGE IT. A MAN NAMED RAYMOND SENT ME THE MSDS.

column168: The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.
